 font-size:12pt">18%</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">. The fall is particularly marked among clinically qualified academics</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">, where women con</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">stitute only 13% of the Professorial cohort.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">We believe that the causes of smaller </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">numbers of women in STEM</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> academi</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">a further up the career ladder are many, involving individual, institutional and wider societal disincentives to careers in science. </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Factor</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">s </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">ontributing to this attrition include the need for women to take more career breaks, inadequacy and expense of childcare provision, institutional </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">inflexibility, and poor provision of appraisal and mentoring opportunities (the latter applying equally to </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">men).</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">A variety of approaches and initiatives is therefore necessary per institution to address particular issues. These require development, </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">creativity, </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">both local and national </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">resourcing</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> and ongoing evaluation.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Preservation of science funding</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">, and </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">increasing flexibility of its availability, are</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> essential to underpinning efforts to retain the best individuals</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; font-variant:small-caps">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:7.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">This submission is made by </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">the University of Cambridge School of Clinical Medicine's Athena SWAN </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Governance G</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">roup</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> The School</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> has been aware </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">for</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> some years of the undoubted attrition of talented females </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">from</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> both clinical and non-clinical academic and research </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">career paths</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">, and </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">has sought to address this by means of a wide-ranging set of in</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">tiatives.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">The umbrella for this is our</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> Athena SWAN project.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:7.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Over the past 3 years, approximately 50% of </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">both </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">undergraduates </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">and graduate students </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">entering the Clinical School have been women, compared to </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">18%</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">who are women </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">at Professorial level. This fall is much more marked among clinical academics, where women constitute only of </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">13% </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">of our </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Professors.</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">In April 2013 the School applied for a Silver level </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Athena SWAN </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">award (outcome awaited)</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">, having begun to address this attri</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">tion in female num</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">bers in 2010 with the establish</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">ment of a Senior Academic Women’s Forum. Further examples of our Athena SWAN initiatives can be found in point </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">15</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; font-variant:small-caps">Why do women leave </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; font-variant:small-caps">STEMM </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; font-variant:small-caps">academia?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:7.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">We believe that the</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">re are a variety of reasons for</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">smaller </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">numbers of women in STEM</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> academi</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">a further up the career ladder, involving individual, institutional and wider societal disincentives</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> to careers in science</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:7.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">An important factor is the inevitable loss of productivity and progress imposed by a perio</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">d of </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">maternity</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> leave. </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Women generally have more and longer career breaks than men. </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">If </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> mother returns to work early, </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">the potential for under-performance</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">compared to colleagues </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">is likely to be compounded by lack of sleep when children are small.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:7.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Women are</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> more likely to take responsibility for providing care, whether this is of children or (increasingly) of ageing parents. Such responsibility may be full or part time, may be predictable or in response to crises, and may be local or distant.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">This is closely</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> aligned to the inadequacy or insufficiency </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">and high cost </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">of child- and/or elderly-care. For example, there are long waiting lists for the University of Cambridge’s nursery scheme.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:7.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">In some scientific careers, there is an expectation that people will </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">m</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">ove</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">around </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">at different stages in their training (eg for postdoctoral research training). </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">When a woman is not single or has dependents, her geographical mobility to progress her career may be constrained</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> more than that of a similarly-qualified male</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> Conversely</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">, women may be more flexible and open to considering alternative career choices.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:7.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">In some cases, women are in ‘dual-</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">scientific-</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">career’ relationships, which may involve either an imbalance in career level or competition for career progression.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> It is less li</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">kely that this will favour the female partner</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:7.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">In </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">parallel, and in </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">comparison to male colleagues, women may lack </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">the confidence to apply for</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> promotion or more senior employment. </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">There </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> also </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">often</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> a paucity of senior female role models.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> In Cambridge's School of Clinical Medicine, only three Heads of the 17 Departments and embedded Institutes are women.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:7.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">There is a financial disincentive to careers in science</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> as salaries cannot compete with other professions. </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">The undoubted gender pay gap, although diminishing in Cambridge, is an additional </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">disincentive</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> for women.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> These factors are to some extent mitigated when the individual is a clinical academic holding an honorary consultant contract, who will be paid a clin</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">ical salary.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> However, the majority of these individuals are clinically active, which potentially detracts from their scientific contribution.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:1.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">There is an unfortunate persistence in some quarters of historical preconceptions concerning women</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">, including di</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">fferential expectations of men and women’s</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">potential, and inflexibility concerning hours, part-time working, job shares, leave etc. </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Productivity at the h</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">ighest level is often seen as simply less achievable on a less-than-full-time time basis. </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">This can lead</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> to a lack of support and guidance by senior figures. </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Such biases may be conscious or unconscious</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">We believe however that these attitudes and behaviours are diminishing with increased management/leadership training, and natural turnover of senior staff.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:1.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">For clinical academics in training, the competing demands of completing higher training and gaining competitive fellowships may be rendered more difficult to navigate if deaneries and/or senior clinicians lack a flexible approach with sufficient protected</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> research time.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">This is compounded by the generally poor availability of 'bridging' funding to allow clinical academic trainees to move between career stages if they are out of step with standard application deadlines. </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">In addition, an NHS job may be seen a</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">s a 'safer' option.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; font-variant:small-caps">What are the consequences?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:1.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">The consequences of scientifically trained women applying their skills in </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">other</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> employment sectors may be positive:</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li s